HAuing placed your staffe as you be often instructed before,vide lib, 2, ca, 36
                   then put the site in the right leg at what parts you will, as at 44 parts; then make obseruation at the first station, and note the parts cut by site in the left legge; then go * backe a certaine space, as 30 féete, drawing backe the site in the left leg, vntill againe the right site and hee agrée in one line with the altitude: note there also the parts included betwixt the place where your site was at the first station, and where he now is;

which let be 23 parts: then if 23 giue 30, 44. shall giue 57 féet, and 9/23.

Let the maltangle be F F G G, and Z Y X W, then make a point somewhere about the middest, as at A; from whence vnto each corner produce right lines, as A FF, A GG, A &, A Z, and so round as you see in the figure (of the seuenth probleme
                        •
                     ) then take any line, let it be A W, and let the proposition be as 3 to 4: finde a line which shall be to A W as 3 to 4, & so as before find the meane proportion, which count in the line A W, as A F. then from the point F draw a line parallel to W X, as F E, and from the point E draw a line parallel X Y, as E D, and so goe round about, so haue you inscribed a lesser tryangulate HH II, B C D E F, like and proportionall to FF GG, and Z Y X W, the greater tryangulate, that is as 3 to 4.

Kéeping our selues vnto the former angles and termes, first substract the angle B D C, from 180, so haue you the obtuse angle A D B 134 degrées, by the 30 Pro. Chap. 2
                        •

                   or all is one to adde the angle D B C 44 degrées, to the angle B C D 90 degrées, and there shall resulte the same angle A D B 834 deg. afterward adde the angle A D B 134, to B A C 29 degrées, 40 min. the totall of which take from 180, so haue you the angle A D B 16 deg. 20 min. then say;
